tiveness of Oiticica’s participatory works stems not from a renunciation of art, but rather from their ability to produce epistemological models that reimagine the traditional boundaries between art and life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aArtistszBrazilvBiography. 0aOiticica, Haelio - Criticism and interpretation. 7aART / General.2bisacsh  aart, artists, artistic, brazil, brazilian, 20th century, participatory, participation, geometric abstraction, modernization, modernism, modernity, painting, color, spectator, archival research, progress, criticism, interpretation, visual, visualization, sculptor, performance artist, neo-concrete movement, innovative, environmental, environment, latin america.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226260334423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226260334/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles